rary readings, suggesting, for example, that in the post-9/11 era, Moby-Dick may be rewardingly read as a revenge tragedy. Donoghue extends an irresistible invitation to open the pages of these American classics again, demonstrating with wit and acuity how very much they have to say to us now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etcx19th century. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aCanon (Literature) 0aCanon (Literature). 0aChefs-d'œuvre (Littérature). 0aLittérature américainexHistoire et critiquexThéorie, etcx19e siècle. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133783423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300133783.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles